COMP2011 Lab 3

A Caesar ciphar disk used to encrypt and decrypt messages. (from Wikipedia)

In this lab, we are going to revisit functions and file I/O in C++ by implementing the encryption and decryption algorithm of Caesar cipher with digraph coding.

Introduction

Caesar cipher is one of the simplest and most widely known encryption techniques named after Julius Caesar, who used it to send private messages. In this method, each letter in the given text is replaced by a letter some fixed number of positions down the alphabet. In this lab, we only consider the English alphabet, which contains 26 different letters. By representing capital letters A~Z by numbers 0~25, encryption of a letter x by a shift (i.e. key) n can be described mathematically as:

    E(x,n)=(x+n)mod26

For example, with a shift of 3, A would be replaced by D, B would become E, and so on. Decryption is performed similarly if the shift n is known:

    D(x,n)=(x−n)mod26

However, Caesar cipher is not secure enough because there are only 26 possible keys. To make the cipher more secure, we can use digraph coding, where the text is encrypted in pairs of letters instead of single letters. The encryption and decryption functions are similar to the orginal Caesar cipher, but the input and output are digraphs instead of single letters. Digraph coding can be described as:

    C(x,y)=26x+y, where x and y are the numerical values of the two letters in the digraph.

For example, "BA" is mapped to a number 26 * 1 + 0 = 26 based on digraph coding. With digraph coding, the number of possible keys increases from 26 in the original Caesar cipher to 26^2 = 676 possible shifts. This makes the new cipher much more secure.

The process to convert the encrypted number back to a digraph is already implemented for you, so you can focus on the digraph-to-number conversion only.

Tasks

In this lab, you are given a skeleton code which contains

  • two tool functions already implemented:
    • number_to_digraph(): convert an integer number to a digraph
    • numbers_to_text(): convert two integer numbers to a 4-letter text
  • five functions to be implemented by you:
    • digraph_to_number(): convert a digraph to an integer number
    • encrypt_digraph_to_number(): encrypt a digraph into an integer number
    • encrypt_text_to_numbers(): encrypt a 4-letter text into two integer numbers
    • decrypt_digraph_to_number(): decrypt a digraph into an integer number
    • decrypt_text_to_numbers(): decrypt a 4-letter text into two integer numbers
  • a main function where you are expected to self-study and use File I/O to read characters and integer numbers from specific text files

Before you start the lab, please

  • download this zip file containing skeleton code and test cases.
  • read the self-study topic FILE I/O

Task 1: Digraph Coding

Complete the implementation of digraph_to_number() for digraph coding.

digraph_to_number(char c1, char c2): map c1 and c2 to numbers in range [0, 25] both inclusive, then compute the numerical representation of the digraph based on digraph coding.
e.g. digraph_to_number('C', 'O') returns 66, digraph_to_number('M', 'P') returns 327.

Task 2: Encryption

Complete the implementation of the functions, encrypt_digraph_to_number() and encrypt_text_to_numbers() to encrypt a 4-letter text into two integer numbers.

  • encrypt_digraph_to_number(char c1, char c2, int key): use digraph_to_number() to represent the input digraph (c1, c2) as an integer number, then encrypt it based on Caesar cipher with the given key.
    e.g. encrypt_digraph_to_number('C', 'O', 11) returns 77, encrypt_digraph_to_number('M', 'P', 11) returns 338.

  • encrypt_text_to_numbers(char c1, char c2, char c3, char c4, int key, int& num1, int& num2): use encrypt_digraph_to_number() to encrypt (c1, c2) and (c3, c4) into two integer numbers num1, num2 with the given key.
    e.g. encrypt_text_to_numbers('C', 'O', 'M', 'P', 11, num1, num2) updates num1=77 and num2=338, encrypt_text_to_numbers('Y', 'E', 'A', 'H', 600, num1, num2) updates num1=552 and num2=607.

Task 3: Decryption

Complete the implementation of the functions, decrypt_digraph_to_number() and decrypt_text_to_numbers() to decrypt a 4-letter text into two integer numbers.

  • decrypt_digraph_to_number(char c1, char c2, int key): use digraph_to_number() to represent the input digraph (c1, c2) as an integer number, and then decrypt it based on Caesar cipher with the given key.
    e.g. decrypt_digraph_to_number('C', 'Z', 11) returns 66, decrypt_digraph_to_number('N', 'A', 11) returns 327.

  • decrypt_text_to_numbers(char c1, char c2, char c3, char c4, int key, int& num1, int& num2): use decrypt_digraph_to_number() to decrypt (c1, c2) and (c3, c4) into two integer numbers num1, num2 with the given key.
    e.g. decrypt_text_to_numbers('C', 'Z', 'N', 'A', 11, num1, num2) updates num1=66 and num2=327, decrypt_text_to_numbers('V', 'G', 'X', 'J', 600, num1, num2) updates num1=628 and num2=7.

Task 4: Read Files

Complete the code in the main function to read characters and integer numbers from an input file line by line.

The first line read from the file is a number representing the option: 1 for encryption and 2 for decryption. The 2-5th lines are four characters representing a 4-letter text, and the 6th line is a number representing the key.

After reading the input file, you need to close the file stream.

Important Notes

  • You can assume that option is either 1 or 2, c1, c2, c3 and c4 are restricted to capital letters, and key lies in the range [0, 675] both inclusive. This means that you don't need to check invalid inputs.
  • You can also assume that all input files are valid.
  • To map a character c to an integer number in [0, 25], the easiest way is to compute c - 'A'. Recall that char type variables in C++ are numbers in nature.
  • You must keep the order of c1, c2, c3 and c4. In other words, the decrypted text should has the same permutation of letters as the original text.
  • You are strongly recommended to use the constants provided in the skeleton code instead of writing literal numbers to avoid possible mistakes.
  • Please write your code only in designated areas. Do not modify the other parts of the skeleton code.

Checking Before Submission

Please use the following methods to accurately check your program output against the sample output. It avoids simple mistakes (e.g., typo mistakes) that cause marks deduction in ZINC.

Please compare your outputs with the desired outputs:

  • In VSCode, please open the terminal by one of the following two ways:
    • Press the key Ctrl+Shift+` in Windows/Linux, or Control+Shift+Backquote in Mac
    • From the menubar, select Terminal > New Terminal
    And then run this code to compile your code: 
    g++ -std=c++11 lab3.cpp -o lab3
  • You need to redirect the input of executable program to the txt test case files we provided, and redirect the output to different txt files. Here are the commands:
    • In MacOS or Linux: 
      ./lab3 > myOutput1.txt
    • In Windows: 
      ./lab3 > myOutput1.txt
    • [Important]: Since Lab3 is about file I/O, we do not provide files for input redirection to avoid possible confusion. After running the above commands, the terminal will display nothing and wait for your input, then please enter the path of the input file manually: 
      testcase/input1.txt
      An example of the complete terminal display is shown below:

    Please replace the filenames accordingly if you would like to check other output files.

  • After that, you can compare your own output text files with the desired outputs one by one. You can compare any two files by VSCode:
    • Right click the first file you want to compare in VSCode Explorer, choose Select for Compare
    • Right click the second file you want to compare in VSCode Explorer, choose Compare with Selected

Grading Scheme

Each lab carries 3 points in total.

  • A student gets 1 point for attendance.
  • A student gets 1 point for a successful ZINC submission (lab3.cpp, the filename is case-sensitive)
    • The ZINC submission deadline is 10 minutes after your lab class. For example, if the lab end time is 12:50PM, the ZINC submission deadline is 01:00PM (i.e., 10 minutes after 12:50PM) on the same day.
  • A student gets 1 point for the Q&A session with the TA
    • The list of selected students will only be shown during the lab class.
    • If the student is not selected for the Q&A, then the ZINC submission will count for 2 points.
      • Some examples:
        • If a student attended the lab, was not selected in Q and A, and passed all test cases in ZINC.
          1 (from attendance) + 1 (from ZINC) * 2 = 3 marks
        • If a student attended the lab, was not selected in Q and A, and passed half (50%) of the test cases in ZINC.
          1 (from attendance) + 0.5 (from ZINC) * 2 = 2 marks
        • If a student attended the lab, was not selected in Q and A, and failed all test cases in ZINC.
          1 (from attendance) + 0 (from ZINC) * 2 = 1 mark
  • The filename is lab3.cpp, and submit it to ZINC. 50% penalty will be given if your filename is wrong.
  • You don't need to zip the file if you only submit one file to ZINC. Filename checking is enabled in ZINC. If your filename is wrong, you should see something like this:

If a student is unable to finish the lab and demonstrate to the TA by the end of the lab, they can only get the attendance point.
